# Git: never commit or push

**Do not run `git commit`, `git push`, or any command that creates or publishes commits** for this repository unless the user explicitly asks you to in that message.

This includes:

- Initial commits or “helping” publish the repo to GitHub
- Committing fixes, rules, or docs “while you’re at it”
- Pushing after a commit the user did not request

When git work is needed without an explicit commit request:

- Explain what changed and tell the user which commands to run themselves
- You may run read-only git commands (`git status`, `git diff`, `git log`) to answer questions

The user is the sole author of this repository. Agent-created commits pollute GitHub contributor history and must not happen.
